<subSubSection id="0ABEFAFFFF9DC118B9FB246BFE45FAFD" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="421BA974FF9DC118B9FB246BFE45FAFD" blockId="19.[151,1437,366,1365]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis id="70D07566FF9DC118B9FB246BFE83FA99" bold="true" box="[199,334,1303,1329]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is derived from the Latin 
<emphasis id="70D07566FF9DC118BA6A246BFC55FA98" box="[854,920,1303,1328]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">ventr-</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis id="70D07566FF9DC118BAF2246BFB8CFA99" box="[974,1089,1303,1329]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">maculatus</emphasis>
, referring to the forewing with a spot on the dorsum.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
